I needed a couple of days to process the amount of emotions after last Hubdot event on Thursday the 7th. People connecting through their stories. It sounds simple and it should be but it simply isn't. When did we share what we went through with someone? When did we feel so safe and in good hands that we truly opened up and said out loud not only the joyful bits but also the painful ones? When did we dare say our truth even if it was a bubble of emotions including those ones - like shame and anger - that made us feel uncomfortable? When did we do that with complete strangers, trusting that would be welcome and accepted somehow by someone we've never met before? When? Well, we should do it. More. And more. Grazie @hubdot for being my favourite playground.
Thank you @askalondon for turning me and Alice in African queens for a night, we felt the power of the Big Mama. Thank you @thewornoutproject for the amazing t-shirt. You told me "wear it and enjoy it". I definitely am.

#alchemy #storytelling #truth #connection #stayhuman #layers #hubdot #hubdotevents #hubdotlondon #authentic #fear #dare #support #real

It's World Mental Health Day today. I never thought in my life I would suffer from depression, but I did and every now and then still do. Moving to a new country was more challenging than I expected and still today, after 5 years and a half, a part of me is constantly homesick. But it has been an incredible journey to explore all the things I could do to feel better and reconnect to myself. Books, therapies, movies, people. My mental health is a work in progress, and I am still working on it. Some days it feels like drowning a bit, but then I remember how great I am at swimming. 
Photo by @veronicaonofriweddingreportage
